lish Digital Icon' @milokmat \u2665\ufe0f #LastNight\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n|-\n|2020\n|Grazia \n|Cool List\n|{{won}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|9933392}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCvCyIiKSCA1fHKSCOKJyjXA Mostly Sane Youtube Channel]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koli, Prajakta}}\n[[Category:Indian YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Female YouTubers]]\n__FORCETOC__\n[[Category:Indian comedians]]\n", "name_user": "IRoyalYadav", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prajakta_Koli"}
{"title_page": "Fred Turner (musician)", "text_new": "{{Use Canadian English|date=March 2016}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name                 = Fred Turner\n|image                = BachmanTurner Mod Club (CMFCMW) March 11, 2011 - Fred Turner.jpg\n|landscape            = yes\n|caption              = Fred Turner performing in 2011. Photo by Zack Lovatt.\n|image_size           =\n|background           = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Charles Frederick Turner\n| alias               = C.F. Turner\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1943|10|16}}\n| birth_place         = [[Winnipeg]], Manitoba, Canada\n| origin              = \n| death_date          = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place         = \n|instrument           = Vocals, bass<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n|genre                = Rock, [[hard rock]]\n|occupation           = Musician, songwriter, actor\n|years_active         = 1970\u2013present\n|label                =\n|associated_acts      = [[Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive]], Pink Plumm, [[Brave Belt]], The D-Drifters, [[Randy Murray]], [[Little River Band]] \n|website              = {{URL|bachmanandturner.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Charles Frederick Turner''' (born October 16, 1943) is a Canadian rock bassist, vocalist and songwriter, and was a founding member of the 1970s rock band [[Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive]] (B.T.O.).  He is credited on most Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive and B.T.O. albums as \"C.F. Turner\".\n\n== History ==\nFred Turner played in over a dozen bands in and around [[Winnipeg]] during his early adult years, his first vocal recordings being with the group Pink Plumm, which released one independent single. Based upon advice [[Randy Bachman]] received from [[Neil Young]], Turner was subsequently asked to join Randy's band [[Brave Belt]] in 1971.<ref>\"Driving Music: Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive,\" article at www.allpar.com</ref> At the time, Turner was playing and singing in a cover band called the D-Drifters. The D-Drifters wanted to continue doing cover songs, and had repeatedly rejected Turner's original compositions. When the call came from Bachman, Turner jumped at the chance to join a band that played original material.<ref name=\"BTO-FAQ\">Gormley, Peter. \"BTO (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive) Frequently Asked Questions,\" 7/31/97.</ref>\n\nThe lead vocalist for the first Brave Belt album was [[Chad Allan (musician)|Chad Allan]], Randy Bachman's former bandmate from [[The Guess Who]]. While shopping around the tapes to record companies and eventually getting interest from Reprise Records, Randy was required to list the band members for contracts. Although he had played both lead guitar and bass on the recording, Randy listed Turner as the bassist. Turner's photo was put on the ''Brave Belt'' back cover, but he was not involved in the recordings. Soon, Turner stepped in as a full-time lead vocalist and bassist, which led to the departure of Allen.<ref name=\"BTO-FAQ\"/> Fred contributed five song compositions to the follow-up ''Brave Belt II'' album (1972), and he sang lead vocal on nine of the album's eleven songs. While shopping around a proposed \"Brave Belt III\" album, the band changed its name to Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive (BTO). Although Randy Bachman was the more widely known name because of his years with The Guess Who, [[Robbie Bachman]] stated in numerous interviews that there could have been no \"BTO sound\" without Turner's contributions: \"The first Brave Belt album was very country-rock. Everything changed when Fred joined the band. We had Fred Turner's heavy, rough voice. We evolved because of Mr. Turner.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorkwaste.com/nyw_main/music/MarkAfterDark/markdark02.html |title=''Mark After Dark'' interview with B.T.O. drummer Rob Bachman, \"Behind the Four Wheel Drive\" |publisher=Newyorkwaste.com |accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\nTurner and BTO enjoyed a period of peak popularity between 1973 and 1976, which saw the band release five Top 40 albums and six US Top 40 singles (eleven in Canada). When Randy Bachman left Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive in late 1977, Turner switched from bass to rhythm guitar to make room for bassist\u2013vocalist [[Jim Clench]]. This new line-up for 1978\u201379 was only called B.T.O. and nothing else, due to legal issues surrounding the use of the Bachman surname. After two albums and supporting tours, this version of B.T.O. called it quits in early 1980. Turner resumed his original role on the bass upon rejoining Randy Bachman in a band called Union, which released a 1981 album titled ''On Strike''. Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive then re-formed for a [[Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive (1984 album)|1984 album]] and subsequent tour.\n\n{{Quote box|width=28%|align=left|quote=\"Turner's songwriting and nimble bass guitar work provide a groovy foundation, but his greatest strength is his voice. His ragged rumble is truly a voice built for rock & roll.\"|source=\u2014Bret Adams, ''Allmusic''.<ref>Adams, Bret [http://www.allmusic.com/album/live-at-the-roseland-ballroom-nyc-mw0002347934 Bachman & Turner, Live At The Roseland Ballroom, NYC] at ''Allmusic''</ref>}}Turner is the lead vocalist on many of Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive's most popular tracks, including \"[[Roll On Down the Highway]],\" \"[[Let It Ride (Bachman-Turner Overdrive song)|Let It Ride]],\" \"Blue Collar,\" \"Four Wheel Drive,\" \"Not Fragile\" and \"[[Take It Like a Man (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive song)|Take It Like a Man]].\"  His songwriting credits include \"Gimme Your Money Please,\" \"Blue Collar,\" \"Not Fragile,\" \"Take It Like a Man\" (with [[Blair Thornton]]), \"Let it Ride\" (with Randy Bachman) and \"Roll On Down the Highway\" (with Robbie Bachman). Turner also wrote and sang the lead on \"Heartaches\" (1979), the lone B.T.O. single to chart in the post-Randy Bachman era.\n\nTurner recorded a solo song for the ''Animal Magnetism'' CD called \"Walk With You\" in 1996. The ''Animal Magnetism'' album was put together by [[Riff West]]. Other musicians that recorded songs for this album include [[Dave Peverett|Lonesome Dave Peverett]] of [[Foghat]], [[Pat Travers]], and [[Edgar Winter]].  In 2000, he made a voice appearance with Randy Bachman on an episode of ''The Simpsons''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snpp.com/episodes/BABF09 |title=Saddlesore Galatica |publisher=Snpp.com |accessdate=July 17, 2014}}</ref>  \n\nTurner's last performance on stage with any formation of BTO was in 2004 with Randy Murray. The two were backed by members of the [[Little River Band]] because drummer [[Robbie Bachman]] and guitarist [[Blair Thornton]] were unable to attend BTO's last show. Turner is the only member of Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive to be on every album the band released.\n\n==2010 Bachman and Turner reunion==\nTurner reunited with Randy Bachman and recorded a new [[Bachman & Turner (Album)|self-titled album]] that was released in September 2010 under the name \"[[Bachman & Turner]].\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Sterdan |first=Darryl |url=http://www.winnipegsun.com/entertainment/columnists/darryl_sterdan/2009/12/06/12061376-sun.html |title=Bachman and Turner return |publisher=Winnipegsun.com |date=December 7, 2009 |accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bachmanandturner.com |title=BTO official biography |publisher=Bachmanandturner.com |date= |accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref> Originally, Randy was developing a solo album and asked Fred to be a guest vocalist on one track called \"Rock n\u2019 Roll is the Only Way Out\". However, after Fred sent back the track with his voice added, Randy was so impressed at how well the vocals fit the music, he decided to scrap his solo effort in favor of a full-on collaboration with Turner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gibson.com/en-us/Lifestyle/Features/randy-bachman-0611/ |title=The Gibson Interview: Randy Bachman (Part 1) |publisher=Gibson.com |date= |accessdate=November 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBachman and Turner embarked on a 2010\u201311 world tour in support of their 2010 album, though numerous BTO songs were also played in their live set. The B&T world tour opened in June 2010 at the [[Sweden Rock Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bachmanandturner.com/btmain.php?ch=bio|title=Bachman & Turner|website=www.bachmanandturner.com|access-date=May 29, 2019}}</ref> The two continued on-and-off concert tours for several more years until, in March 2018, Randy Bachman announced that Turner would be retiring from touring.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/entertainment/randy-bachman-says-bto-bandmate-fred-turner-will-retire-from-touring-1.3838468 |title=Randy Bachman says BTO bandmate Fred Turner will retire from touring |date=March 11, 2018 |accessdate=July 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition and other achievements==\n* 1974: [[Juno Award]] winner, ''Most Promising Group of the Year''\n* 1975: Juno Award winner, ''Group of the Year''\n* 1976: Juno Award winner, ''Group of the Year''\n* 1978: Juno Award nomination, ''Group of the Year''\n* 2008: Guitar Magazine, ''Takin' Care of Business rated at number 10 in top 100 most covered songs''\n* 2009: iTunes, ''Takin' Care of Business is the most downloaded song on iTunes''\n\n==Discography==\nAll releases by Bachman-Turner Overdrive/BTO unless otherwise noted.\n\n;Studio albums\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! U.S. certification<ref name=\"riaa.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.riaa.org |title=Recording Industry Association of America |publisher=RIAA |date= |accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref>\n! Chart number\n|-\n|1973\n|''[[Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive (1973 album)|Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive]]'' \n| Gold\n| 70\n|-\n|1973\n|''[[Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive II]]'' \n| Gold\n| 4\n|-\n|1974\n|''[[Not Fragile]]'' \n| Gold\n| 1\n|-\n|1975\n|''[[Four Wheel Drive (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive album)|Four Wheel Drive]]''\n| Gold\n| 5\n|-\n|1975\n|''[[Head On (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive album)|Head On]]'' \n| Gold\n| 21\n|-\n|1977\n|''[[Freeways (album)|Freeways]]'' \n| \u2013\n| 70\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[Street Action]]'' \n| \u2013\n| 135\n|-\n|1979\n|''[[Rock n' Roll Nights]]''\n| \u2013\n| 165\n|-\n|1981\n|''On Strike'' (Union)\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive (1984 album)|Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive]]''\n| \u2013\n| 87\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Trial By Fire: Greatest and Latest]]''\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Bachman & Turner]]'' (Bachman & Turner)\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|}\n\n;Live albums\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! U.S. certification\n! Chart number\n|-\n|1977\n|''[[B.T.O. Live \u2013 Japan Tour]]'' \n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Live Live Live]]'' \n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Best of Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive Live]]'' \n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Motorcity Detroit USA Live]]'' \n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[King Biscuit Flower Hour: Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive]]'' \n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Live at the Roseland Ballroom, NYC]]'' (Bachman & Turner) \n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|}\n\n;Compilation albums\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! U.S. certification<ref name=\"riaa.org\"/>\n! Chart number\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[Best of BTO (So Far)]]''\n| Platinum\n| 19\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[You Ain't Seen Nothing Yet (album)|You Ain't Seen Nothing Yet]]''\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[BTO's Greatest]]''\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[The Anthology (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive album)|The Anthology]]'' \n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1998\n|''Takin' Care of Business''\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|2000\n|''20th Century Masters: The Millennium Collection: The Best of Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive''\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[The Very Best of Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive]]''\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive Gold]]'' \n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|}\n'''Singles'''<ref name=allmusic1>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist |id=p53348/charts-awards/billboard-singles |pure_url=yes}} |title=Bachman-Turner Overdrive |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Single\n!Chart\n!Position\n|-\n|1973\n|\"Blue Collar\"\n|Rock Singles\n|68\n|-\n|1974\n|\"[[Let It Ride (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive song)|Let It Ride]]\"\n|Pop Singles\n|23\n|-\n|1974\n|\"[[Takin' Care of Business (song)|Takin' Care of Business]]\"\n|\n|12\n|-\n|1974\n|\"[[You Ain't Seen Nothing Yet (Bachman-Turner Overdrive song)|You Ain't Seen Nothing Yet]]\"\n|\n|1\n|-\n|1974\n|\"[[Roll On down the Highway|Roll on Down The Highway]]\"\n|\n|14\n|-\n|1975\n|\"[[Hey You (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive song)|Hey You]]\"\n|\n|21\n|-\n|1976\n|\"[[Down to the Line (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive song)|Down to the Line]]\"\n|\n|43\n|-\n|1976\n|\"[[Take It Like a Man (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive song)|Take It Like a Man]]\"\n|\n|33\n|-\n|1976\n|\"[[Lookin\u2019 Out for No. 1 (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive song)|Lookin' Out For #1]]\"\n|\n|65\n|-\n|1976\n|\"Gimme Your Money Please\"\n|\n|70\n|-\n|1977\n|\"My Wheels Won't Turn\"\n|\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1977\n|\"Shotgun Rider\"\n|\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1978\n|\"Down The Road\"\n|\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1979\n|\"[[Jamaica (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive song)|Jamaica]]\"\n|\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1979\n|\"Heartaches\"\n|\n|60\n|-\n|1984\n|\"Service with a Smile\"\n|\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1984\n|\"For The Weekend\"\n|\n|83\n|-\n|1996\n|\"House of the Rising Sun\"\n|\n| \u2013\n|-\n|2010\n|\"Rollin' Along\" (Bachman & Turner)\n|\n| \u2013\n|}\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Type\n!Title\n|-\n|1974\n|Music Video\n|You Ain't Seen Nothin' Yet\n|-\n|1975\n|Documentary/ Live Shows\n|1975 Road Special\n|-\n|1983\n|Music Video\n|For The Weekend\n|-\n|1988\n|Live Show\n|'88 Reunion\n|-\n|1995\n|Documentary/ Live Shows\n|BTO: The Movie\n|-\n|2012\n|Motion picture\n|[https://m.imdb.com/title/tt1790886/ The Campaign] \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive}}\n {{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turner, Fred}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian rock bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Canadian rock singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive members]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian bass guitarists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Canadian English|date=March 2016}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name                 = Fred Turner\n|image                = BachmanTurner Mod Club (CMFCMW) March 11, 2011 - Fred Turner.jpg\n|landscape            = yes\n|caption              = Fred Turner performing in 2011. Photo by Zack Lovatt.\n|image_size           =\n|background           = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Charles Frederick Turner\n| alias               = C.F. Turner\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1943|10|16}}\n| birth_place         = [[Winnipeg]], Manitoba, Canada\n| origin              = \n| death_date          = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place         = \n|instrument           = Vocals, bass<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n|genre                = Rock, [[hard rock]]\n|occupation           = Musician, songwriter, actor\n|years_active         = 1970\u2013present\n|label                =\n|associated_acts      = [[Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive]], Pink Plumm, [[Brave Belt]], The D-Drifters, [[Randy Murray]], [[Little River Band]] \n|website              = {{URL|bachmanandturner.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Charles Frederick Turner''' (born October 16, 1943) is a Canadian rock bassist, vocalist and songwriter, and was a founding member of the 1970s rock band [[Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive]] (B.T.O.).  He is credited on most Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive and B.T.O. albums as \"C.F. Turner\".\n\n== History ==\nFred Turner played in over a dozen bands in and around [[Winnipeg]] during his early adult years, his first vocal recordings being with the group Pink Plumm, which released one independent single. Based upon advice [[Randy Bachman]] received from [[Neil Young]], Turner was subsequently asked to join Randy's band [[Brave Belt]] in 1971.<ref>\"Driving Music: Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive,\" article at www.allpar.com</ref> At the time, Turner was playing and singing in a cover band called the D-Drifters. The D-Drifters wanted to continue doing cover songs, and had repeatedly rejected Turner's original compositions. When the call came from Bachman, Turner jumped at the chance to join a band that played original material.<ref name=\"BTO-FAQ\">Gormley, Peter. \"BTO (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive) Frequently Asked Questions,\" 7/31/97.</ref>\n\nThe lead vocalist for the first Brave Belt album was [[Chad Allan (musician)|Chad Allan]], Randy Bachman's former bandmate from [[The Guess Who]]. While shopping around the tapes to record companies and eventually getting interest from Reprise Records, Randy was required to list the band members for contracts. Although he had played both lead guitar and bass on the recording, Randy listed Turner as the bassist. Turner's photo was put on the ''Brave Belt'' back cover, but he was not on the recordings. Soon, Turner stepped in as a full-time lead vocalist and bassist, which led to the departure of Allen.<ref name=\"BTO-FAQ\"/> Fred contributed five song compositions to the follow-up ''Brave Belt II'' album (1972), and he sang lead vocal on nine of the album's eleven songs. While shopping around a proposed \"Brave Belt III\" album, the band changed its name to Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive (BTO). Although Randy Bachman was the more widely known name because of his years with The Guess Who, [[Robbie Bachman]] stated in numerous interviews that there could have been no \"BTO sound\" without Turner's contributions: \"The first Brave Belt album was very country-rock. Everything changed when Fred joined the band. We had Fred Turner's heavy, rough voice. We evolved because of Mr. Turner.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorkwaste.com/nyw_main/music/MarkAfterDark/markdark02.html |title=''Mark After Dark'' interview with B.T.O. drummer Rob Bachman, \"Behind the Four Wheel Drive\" |publisher=Newyorkwaste.com |accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\nTurner and BTO enjoyed a period of peak popularity between 1973 and 1976, which saw the band release five Top 40 albums and six US Top 40 singles (eleven in Canada). When Randy Bachman left Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive in late 1977, Turner switched from bass to rhythm guitar to make room for bassist\u2013vocalist [[Jim Clench]]. This new line-up for 1978\u201379 was only called B.T.O. and nothing else, due to legal issues surrounding the use of the Bachman surname. After two albums and supporting tours, this version of B.T.O. called it quits in early 1980. Turner resumed his original role on the bass upon rejoining Randy Bachman in a band called Union, which released a 1981 album titled ''On Strike''. Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive then re-formed for a [[Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive (1984 album)|1984 album]] and subsequent tour.\n\n{{Quote box|width=28%|align=left|quote=\"Turner's songwriting and nimble bass guitar work provide a groovy foundation, but his greatest strength is his voice. His ragged rumble is truly a voice built for rock & roll.\"|source=\u2014Bret Adams, ''Allmusic''.<ref>Adams, Bret [http://www.allmusic.com/album/live-at-the-roseland-ballroom-nyc-mw0002347934 Bachman & Turner, Live At The Roseland Ballroom, NYC] at ''Allmusic''</ref>}}Turner is the lead vocalist on many of Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive's most popular tracks, including \"[[Roll On Down the Highway]],\" \"[[Let It Ride (Bachman-Turner Overdrive song)|Let It Ride]],\" \"Blue Collar,\" \"Four Wheel Drive,\" \"Not Fragile\" and \"[[Take It Like a Man (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive song)|Take It Like a Man]].\"  His songwriting credits include \"Gimme Your Money Please,\" \"Blue Collar,\" \"Not Fragile,\" \"Take It Like a Man\" (with [[Blair Thornton]]), \"Let it Ride\" (with Randy Bachman) and \"Roll On Down the Highway\" (with Robbie Bachman). Turner also wrote and sang the lead on \"Heartaches\" (1979), the lone B.T.O. single to chart in the post-Randy Bachman era.\n\nTurner recorded a solo song for the ''Animal Magnetism'' CD called \"Walk With You\" in 1996. The ''Animal Magnetism'' album was put together by [[Riff West]]. Other musicians that recorded songs for this album include [[Dave Peverett|Lonesome Dave Peverett]] of [[Foghat]], [[Pat Travers]], and [[Edgar Winter]].  In 2000, he made a voice appearance with Randy Bachman on an episode of ''The Simpsons''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snpp.com/episodes/BABF09 |title=Saddlesore Galatica |publisher=Snpp.com |accessdate=July 17, 2014}}</ref>  \n\nTurner's last performance on stage with any formation of BTO was in 2004 with Randy Murray. The two were backed by members of the [[Little River Band]] because drummer [[Robbie Bachman]] and guitarist [[Blair Thornton]] were unable to attend BTO's last show. Turner is the only member of Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive to be on every album the band released.\n\n==2010 Bachman and Turner reunion==\nTurner reunited with Randy Bachman and recorded a new [[Bachman & Turner (Album)|self-titled album]] that was released in September 2010 under the name \"[[Bachman & Turner]].\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Sterdan |first=Darryl |url=http://www.winnipegsun.com/entertainment/columnists/darryl_sterdan/2009/12/06/12061376-sun.html |title=Bachman and Turner return |publisher=Winnipegsun.com |date=December 7, 2009 |accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bachmanandturner.com |title=BTO official biography |publisher=Bachmanandturner.com |date= |accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref> Originally, Randy was developing a solo album and asked Fred to be a guest vocalist on one track called \"Rock n\u2019 Roll is the Only Way Out\". However, after Fred sent back the track with his voice added, Randy was so impressed at how well the vocals fit the music, he decided to scrap his solo effort in favor of a full-on collaboration with Turner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gibson.com/en-us/Lifestyle/Features/randy-bachman-0611/ |title=The Gibson Interview: Randy Bachman (Part 1) |publisher=Gibson.com |date= |accessdate=November 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBachman and Turner embarked on a 2010\u201311 world tour in support of their 2010 album, though numerous BTO songs were also played in their live set. The B&T world tour opened in June 2010 at the [[Sweden Rock Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bachmanandturner.com/btmain.php?ch=bio|title=Bachman & Turner|website=www.bachmanandturner.com|access-date=May 29, 2019}}</ref> The two continued on-and-off concert tours for several more years until, in March 2018, Randy Bachman announced that Turner would be retiring from touring.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/entertainment/randy-bachman-says-bto-bandmate-fred-turner-will-retire-from-touring-1.3838468 |title=Randy Bachman says BTO bandmate Fred Turner will retire from touring |date=March 11, 2018 |accessdate=July 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition and other achievements==\n* 1974: [[Juno Award]] winner, ''Most Promising Group of the Year''\n* 1975: Juno Award winner, ''Group of the Year''\n* 1976: Juno Award winner, ''Group of the Year''\n* 1978: Juno Award nomination, ''Group of the Year''\n* 2008: Guitar Magazine, ''Takin' Care of Business rated at number 10 in top 100 most covered songs''\n* 2009: iTunes, ''Takin' Care of Business is the most downloaded song on iTunes''\n\n==Discography==\nAll releases by Bachman-Turner Overdrive/BTO unless otherwise noted.\n\n;Studio albums\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! U.S. certification<ref name=\"riaa.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.riaa.org |title=Recording Industry Association of America |publisher=RIAA |date= |accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref>\n! Chart number\n|-\n|1973\n|''[[Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive (1973 album)|Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive]]'' \n| Gold\n| 70\n|-\n|1973\n|''[[Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive II]]'' \n| Gold\n| 4\n|-\n|1974\n|''[[Not Fragile]]'' \n| Gold\n| 1\n|-\n|1975\n|''[[Four Wheel Drive (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive album)|Four Wheel Drive]]''\n| Gold\n| 5\n|-\n|1975\n|''[[Head On (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive album)|Head On]]'' \n| Gold\n| 21\n|-\n|1977\n|''[[Freeways (album)|Freeways]]'' \n| \u2013\n| 70\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[Street Action]]'' \n| \u2013\n| 135\n|-\n|1979\n|''[[Rock n' Roll Nights]]''\n| \u2013\n| 165\n|-\n|1981\n|''On Strike'' (Union)\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive (1984 album)|Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive]]''\n| \u2013\n| 87\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Trial By Fire: Greatest and Latest]]''\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Bachman & Turner]]'' (Bachman & Turner)\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|}\n\n;Live albums\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! U.S. certification\n! Chart number\n|-\n|1977\n|''[[B.T.O. Live \u2013 Japan Tour]]'' \n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Live Live Live]]'' \n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Best of Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive Live]]'' \n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Motorcity Detroit USA Live]]'' \n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[King Biscuit Flower Hour: Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive]]'' \n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Live at the Roseland Ballroom, NYC]]'' (Bachman & Turner) \n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|}\n\n;Compilation albums\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! U.S. certification<ref name=\"riaa.org\"/>\n! Chart number\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[Best of BTO (So Far)]]''\n| Platinum\n| 19\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[You Ain't Seen Nothing Yet (album)|You Ain't Seen Nothing Yet]]''\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[BTO's Greatest]]''\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[The Anthology (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive album)|The Anthology]]'' \n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1998\n|''Takin' Care of Business''\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|2000\n|''20th Century Masters: The Millennium Collection: The Best of Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive''\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[The Very Best of Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive]]''\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive Gold]]'' \n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|}\n'''Singles'''<ref name=allmusic1>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist |id=p53348/charts-awards/billboard-singles |pure_url=yes}} |title=Bachman-Turner Overdrive |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Single\n!Chart\n!Position\n|-\n|1973\n|\"Blue Collar\"\n|Rock Singles\n|68\n|-\n|1974\n|\"[[Let It Ride (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive song)|Let It Ride]]\"\n|Pop Singles\n|23\n|-\n|1974\n|\"[[Takin' Care of Business (song)|Takin' Care of Business]]\"\n|\n|12\n|-\n|1974\n|\"[[You Ain't Seen Nothing Yet (Bachman-Turner Overdrive song)|You Ain't Seen Nothing Yet]]\"\n|\n|1\n|-\n|1974\n|\"[[Roll On down the Highway|Roll on Down The Highway]]\"\n|\n|14\n|-\n|1975\n|\"[[Hey You (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive song)|Hey You]]\"\n|\n|21\n|-\n|1976\n|\"[[Down to the Line (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive song)|Down to the Line]]\"\n|\n|43\n|-\n|1976\n|\"[[Take It Like a Man (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive song)|Take It Like a Man]]\"\n|\n|33\n|-\n|1976\n|\"[[Lookin\u2019 Out for No. 1 (Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive song)|Lookin' Out For #1]]\"\n|\n|65\n|-\n|1976\n|\"Gimme Your Money Please\"\n|\n|70\n|-\n|1977\n|\"My Wheels Won't Turn\"\n|\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1977\n|\"Shotgun Rider\"\n|\n| \u2013\n|-\n|1978\n|\"Down The Road\"\n|\