cessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> It wasn\u2019t until on 7 January 2017 when Yoshida scored his first goal of the season, in a 2\u20132 draw against [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] in the third round of the EFL Cup.<ref>{{cite news|title=Norwich City 1\u20132 Southampton|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38474591|publisher=BBC Sport|date=7 January 2017|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> Following the match, he dedicated his goal to his newly born baby daughter.<ref>{{cite news|title= \u201c\u304a\u3057\u3083\u3076\u308a\u30d1\u30d5\u30a9\u201d\u306e\u9ebb\u4e5f\u300c\u8d64\u3061\u3083\u3093\u304c\u30b4\u30fc\u30eb\u3092\u30d7\u30ec\u30bc\u30f3\u30c8\u3057\u3066\u304f\u308c\u305f\u300d|url=https://web.gekisaka.jp/news/detail/?207436-207436-fl |publisher=Web Gekisaka|language=Japanese|date=8 January 2017|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> Yoshida captained the side for the first time in his Southampton\u2019s career, beating Norwich City 1\u20130 in the third round of the FA Cup replay.<ref>{{cite news|title=Southampton 1\u20130 Norwich City|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38579247|publisher=BBC Sport|date=18 January 2017|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> Despite indifferent form on the part of both Yoshida and Southampton as a whole, Southampton became the first team in history to reach the [[2017 EFL Cup Final|the final]] without conceding a single goal after beating [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] 2\u20130 on aggregate in the EFL semi\u2013finals.<ref>{{cite news|title=Southampton 1\u20130 Liverpool|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38504049|publisher=BBC Sport|date=11 January 2017|accessdate=5 April 2020}}<br>{{cite news|title=Liverpool 0\u20131 Southampton|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38659708|publisher=BBC Sport|date=25 January 2017|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> Yoshida previously helped Southampton kept three clean sheets in a built up to the EFL Cup semi\u2013finals.<ref>{{cite news|title=Southampton 2\u20130 Crystal Palace|url=https: