u20130||[[Exhibition game#Association football|Friendly]]\n|-\n!scope=row|4\n|12 January 2015||[[Newcastle International Sports Centre|Newcastle Stadium]], [[Newcastle, New South Wales|Newcastle]], Australia||49||{{fb|PLE}} ||4\u20130||4\u20130||[[2015 AFC Asian Cup Group D|2015 AFC Asian Cup]]\n|-\n!scope=row|5\n|3 September 2015||Saitama Stadium 2002, Saitama, Japan||56||{{fb|CAM}}||2\u20130||3\u20130||rowspan=3|[[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Second Round|2018 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n|-\n!scope=row|6\n|12 November 2015||[[National Stadium, Singapore|National Stadium]], [[Kallang]], Singapore||60||{{fb|SIN}}||3\u20130||3\u20130\n|-\n!scope=row|7\n|24 March 2016||Saitama Stadium 2002, Saitama, Japan||62||{{fb|AFG}}||3\u20130||5\u20130\n|-\n!scope=row|8\n|rowspan=2|3 June 2016||rowspan=2|[[Toyota Stadium]], [[Toyota, Aichi|Toyota]], Japan||rowspan=2|64||rowspan=2|{{fb|BUL}}||4\u20130||rowspan=2|7\u20132||rowspan=2|[[Kirin Cup|2016 Kirin Cup]]\n|-\n!scope=row|9\n|5\u20130\n|-\n!scope=row|10\n|28 March 2017||rowspan=2|Saitama Stadium 2002, Saitama, Japan||73||{{fb|THA}}||4\u20130||4\u20130||[[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Third Round|2018 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n|-\n!scope=row|11\n|10 October 2019||98||{{fb|MNG}}||2\u20130||6\u20130||[[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Second Round|2022 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n|}\n\n==Personal Life==\nYoshida has two brothers: Mirei and Honami<ref name=\"Yoshida Brother\"/> He later credited his older brother, Honami, for playing an important role to his football career.<ref name=\"Yoshida Brother\"/><ref name=\"Yoshida Brother2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.zakzak.co.jp/sports/soccer/news/20140525/soc1405250830002-n1.htm|title=\u3010\uff37\u676f\uff12\uff13\u6226\u58eb\u540d\u9451\uff08\uff16\uff09\u3011\uff24\uff26\u5409\u7530\u9ebb\u4e5f\u3000\u5144\u8cb4\u305f\u3061\u3078\u6069\u3092\u8fd4\u3059\u201c\u5ac1\u306b\u3057\u305f\u3044\u201d\u5f37\u3044\u7537|publisher=Zakzak|language=Japanese|date=25 May 2014|accessdate=5 April 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331193903/http://www.zakzak.co.jp/sports/soccer/news/20140525/soc1405250830002-n1.htm|archivedate=5 April 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> Before he was born, his name \"Maya\" was originally planned for a girl when his mother was pregnant.<ref name=\"Yoshida Brother2\"/> But the name was kept it was a boy who was born.<ref name=\"Yoshida Brother2\"/> Yoshida revealed on his blog on the 26th September 2012 that he\u2019s married to a general woman from Grampus.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u5409\u7530\u9ebb\u4e5f\u3055\u3093\u306e\u30d6\u30ed\u30b0\u3092\u8aad\u3093\u3067\u66f8\u3044\u305f\u7d50\u5a5a\u8a18\u4e8b\u3092\u8aad\u3093\u3067\u304b\u3089\u7d50\u5a5a\u5831\u544a\u30d6\u30ed\u30b0\u3092\u8aad\u3093\u3060\u4ef6\u3002|url=https://news.livedoor.com/article/detail/6992247/?escode=pcmax|publisher=News Livedoor|language=Japanese|date=27 September 2012|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> Four years later, Yoshida revealed he\u2019s a first time father when his wife gave birth to a baby daughter.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u5409\u7530\u9ebb\u4e5f\u304c\u3064\u3044\u306b\u30d1\u30d1\u306b! \u9577\u5973\u8a95\u751f\u3092\u30d6\u30ed\u30b0\u3067\u5831\u544a\u300c\u5b50\u80b2\u3066\u30d6\u30ed\u30b0\u306b\u5909\u308f\u308b\u304b\u3082\u300d|url=https://web.gekisaka.jp/news/detail/?205558-205558-fl|publisher=Web Gekisaka|language=Japanese|date=16 December 2016|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> During his time at Southampton, Yoshida resided in Winchester.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.southamptonfc.com/news/2019-04-08/programme-feature-interview-maya-yoshida-april-2019|title=Feature Interview: Maya Yoshida|publisher=Southampton F.C.|date=8 April 2019|accessdate=5 April 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405162619/https://www.southamptonfc.com/news/2019-04-08/programme-feature-interview-maya-yoshida-april-2019|archivedate=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  After spending seven years at Southampton, Yoshida revealed in an interview with SunSport that he\u2019s a permanent resident in United Kingdom and feel 25 per cent English.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u5409\u7530\u9ebb\u4e5f\u3000\u82f1\u56fd\u306e\u6c38\u4f4f\u6a29\u3092\u53d6\u5f97\u300c\u516c\u5f0f\u306b\u30a4\u30f3\u30b0\u30e9\u30f3\u30c9\u4eba\u306b\u306a\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\u300d\u5728\u82f1\uff16\u5e74\u534a\u3067|url=https://www.sponichi.co.jp/soccer/news/2019/03/10/kiji/20190310s00002021352000c.html|publisher=Sponichi Annex|language=Japanese|date=10 March 2019|accessdate=10 April 2020}}<br>{{cite news|title=\u30a4\u30f3\u30b0\u30e9\u30f3\u30c9\u3067\uff16\u5e74\u534a\u3002\u6c38\u4f4f\u6a29\u53d6\u5f97\u306e \u5409\u7530\u9ebb\u4e5f\u306e\u8a00\u8449\u306f\u30ba\u30b7\u30ea\u3068\u91cd\u3044|url=https://sportiva.shueisha.co.jp/clm/football/wfootball/2019/03/12/_split_25/|publisher=Sportiva Shueisha|language=Japanese|date=12 March 2019|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHis family runs a boarding house in Nagasaki for children who cannot go to high school.<ref name=\"Yoshida Brother2\"/> Growing up, Yoshida revealed he\u2019s a fan of [[Dragon Ball Z]] and had an entire collection until his Dad gave it to charity. Yoshida reflected on this, saying it helped him to think generously and give back to society.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maya Yoshida: 'My dad is the most crazy Japanese man. But his gestures inspired me'|url=https://inews.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/maya-yoshida-southampton-charity-interview-saints-foundation-495708|publisher=iNews|date=16 August 2019|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In November 2007, Yoshida signed for an agency with [[Tetsuro Kiyooka]], a [[FIFA]] Players' Agent ([[Sports agent]]), in hopes of moving to Europe. It worked when he joined VVV-Venlo, three years later after signing for Tetsuro Kiyooka.<ref name=\"Yoshida V-Venlo 2009\"/><ref name=\"Yoshida V-Venlo\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=\u540d\u53e4\u5c4b\u306e19\u6b73DF\u5409\u7530\u304c\u6d77\u5916\u8996\u91ce\u306b\u4ee3\u7406\u4eba\u5951\u7d04|url=https://web.gekisaka.jp/news/detail/?30486-11129-fl|publisher=Web Gekisaka|language=Japanese|date=27 November 2007|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> Since moving to Europe, Yoshida created his personal blog, where he reflected about his experience living and playing in a different continent.<ref>{{cite news|title=\uff36\uff36\uff36\u306e\u5409\u7530\u9ebb\u4e5f\u304c\u30d6\u30ed\u30b0\u958b\u8a2d|url=https://www.nikkansports.com/soccer/world/news/f-sc-tp3-20100320-607997.html|publisher=Nikkan Sports|language=Japanese|date=20 March 2010|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> On every anniversary of the [[Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|Atomic bombings]], which Yoshida is from Nagasaki, he spoke out about the thoughts of the event.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u5409\u7530\u9ebb\u4e5f\u3001\u539f\u7206\u6295\u4e0b70\u5e74\u76ee\u306e\u601d\u3044\u300c\u6226\u4e89\u3001\u539f\u7206\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066\u304d\u3061\u3093\u3068\u5b66\u3093\u3067\u3044\u3053\u3046\u300d|url=https://web.gekisaka.jp/news/detail/?169278-169278-fl |publisher=Web Gekisaka|language=Japanese|date=9 August 2015|accessdate=5 April 2020}}<br>{{cite news|title=\u9577\u5d0e\u51fa\u8eab\u306e\u5409\u7530\u9ebb\u4e5f\u3001\u539f\u7206\u306e\u65e5\u306b\u4e16\u754c\u3078\u30e1\u30c3\u30bb\u30fc\u30b8|url=https://www.nikkansports.com/soccer/japan/news/1869503.html|publisher=Nikkan Sports|language=Japanese|date=9 August 2017|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Yoshida published his first book titled \"Unbeatable Mind\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Maya Yoshida's written about his 'Unbeatable Mind'|url=https://www.dailyecho.co.uk/sport/16248065.maya-yoshidas-written-about-his-unbeatable-mind/|publisher=Southern Daily Echo|date=25 May 2018|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In addition to speaking Japanese, Yoshida is fluent in English since he first studied the language in middle school.<ref name=\"Yoshida Interview1\"/><ref name=\"Yoshida Language\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=\u82f1\u79fb\u7c4d\u306e\u53ef\u80fd\u6027\u5831\u3058\u3089\u308c\u308b\u5ca1\u5d0e\u306b\u9ebb\u4e5f\u300c\u82f1\u8a9e\u306e\u52c9\u5f37\u3092\u300d|url=https://web.gekisaka.jp/news/detail/?155288-155288-fl|publisher=Web Gekisaka|language=Japanese|date=10 January 2015|accessdate=5 April 2020}}<br>{{cite news|title=\u5409\u7530\u9ebb\u4e5f\u304c\u6d41\u66a2\u306a\u82f1\u8a9e\u3092\u62ab\u9732\u3001\u516c\u5f0f\u4f1a\u898b\u3067\u3055\u3059\u304c\u306e\u8a9e\u5b66\u529b\u767a\u63ee|url=https://web.gekisaka.jp/news/detail/?263677-263677-fl|publisher=Web Gekisaka|language=Japanese|date=8 January 2019|accessdate=5 April 2020}}<br>{{cite news|title=\u5148\u767a\u51fa\u5834&\u6c7a\u52dd\u70b9\u3067\u5197\u820c\u306b?\u5409\u7530\u304c\u82f1\u8a9e\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc\u3067\u7b11\u3044\u3092\u8a98\u3046|url=https://web.gekisaka.jp/news/detail/?182504-182504-fl|publisher=Web Gekisaka|language=Japanese|date=7 February 2019|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> Yoshida also began studying Italian and Spanish.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u5409\u7530\u9ebb\u4e5f\u3001\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u3067\u30bb\u30ea\u30a8A\u5ef6\u671f\u3082\u300c\u30d4\u30f3\u30c1\u3092\u30c1\u30e3\u30f3\u30b9\u306b\u3002\u30a4\u30bf\u30ea\u30a2\u8a9e\u306e\u52c9\u5f37\u306b\u52b1\u307f\u305f\u3044\u300d|url=https://web.gekisaka.jp/news/detail/?299604-299604-fl|publisher=Web Gekisaka|language=Japanese|date=12 February 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Yoshida Language\">{{cite news|title=Maya Yoshida interview: 'If people call this success, it is not enough for me'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/maya-yoshida-interview-if-people-call-this-success-it-is-not-enough-for-me-10107108.html|publisher=The Independent|date=12 March 2015|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> On 9 August 2013, it was announced that Yoshida would be on the front cover of the Japanese Edition of [[FIFA 14]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saintsfc.co.uk/news/article/saints-agree-partnership-with-ea-sports-979983.aspx|title=Saints agree partnership with EA SPORTS|publisher=Southampton F.C.|date=9 August 2013|accessdate=9 August 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130811163234/http://www.saintsfc.co.uk/news/article/saints-agree-partnership-with-ea-sports-979983.aspx|archivedate=5 April 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> During his Japan\u2019s career, Yoshida said he considered [[Atsuto Uchida]] as fellow competitor, yet his best friend, and friends with [[Eiji Kawashima]].<ref>{{cite news|title=\u9ebb\u4e5f\u304c\u5185\u7530\u306b\u30b8\u30a7\u30e9\u30b7\u30fc\u300c\u5185\u7530\u9078\u624b\u306e\u6c7a\u52dd\u70b9\u3067\u8a66\u5408\u304c\u6c7a\u307e\u308b\u65e5\u304c\u6765\u308b\u3068\u306f\u2026\u300d|url=https://web.gekisaka.jp/news/detail/?139741-139741-fl|publisher=Web Gekisaka|language=Japanese|date=27 May 2014|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Yoshida Language\"/> In the wake of [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Yoshida posted a message on his social media account, urging people to stay at home.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u4e3b\u5c06\u30fb\u5409\u7530\u9ebb\u4e5f\u304c\u65e5\u672c\u56fd\u6c11\u306b\u8b66\u9418\u300c\u5197\u8ac7\u629c\u304d\u3067\u5bb6\u306b\u3044\u305f\u65b9\u304c\u826f\u3044\u300d|url=https://web.gekisaka.jp/news/detail/?300237-300237-fl|publisher=Web Gekisaka|language=Japanese|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> Yoshida has an uncle, [[Tsuyoshi Shimoyanagi]], who is a former professional baseball player.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u5409\u7530\u9ebb\u4e5f\u304cSNS\u306b\u3066\u610f\u5916\u306a\u4eba\u7269\u30682\u30b7\u30e7\u30c3\u30c8\u2026\u300c\u89aa\u621a\u306e\u300e\u304a\u5144\u3055\u3093\u300f\u300d|url=https://web.gekisaka.jp/news/detail/?255124-255124-fl|publisher=Web Gekisaka|language=Japanese|date=24 September 2018|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> He is also a part-owner of Soccer Samurai.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u3010\u30a4\u30f3\u30b0\u30e9\u30f3\u30c9\u3011\u30d5\u30c3\u30c8\u30dc\u30fc\u30eb\u30fb\u30b5\u30e0\u30e9\u30a4\u30a2\u30ab\u30c7\u30df\u30fc|url=https://www.europlus.jp/article/samuraiacademy/|publisher=Europlus|language=Japanese|date=25 January 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Yoshida revealed that he was pledging one percent of his salary to a pledge-based charitable movement, named Saints Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.southamptonfc.com/news/2019-08-14/maya-yoshida-saints-foundation-pledge-announcement|title=Yoshida makes Saints Foundation pledge|publisher=Southampton F.C.|date=14 August 2019|accessdate=5 April 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405164117/https://www.southamptonfc.com/news/2019-08-14/maya-yoshida-saints-foundation-pledge-announcement |archivedate=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Two months later, Yoshida was named ambassador for the Saints\u2019 Foundation along with teammate [[James Ward-Prowse]].<ref>{{cite news|title=James Ward-Prowse and Maya Yoshida sign up to Saints Foundation Ambassador Programme|url=https://www.dailyecho.co.uk/sport/17945695.james-ward-prowse-maya-yoshida-sign-saints-foundation-ambassador-programme/|publisher=Southern Daily Echo|date=3 October 2019|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Southampton'''\n*[[EFL Cup]] runner-up: [[2016\u201317 EFL Cup|2016\u201317]]<ref name=\"Yoshida Manchester United\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39018813 |title=Manchester United 3\u20132 Southampton |first=Phil |last=McNulty |publisher=BBC Sport |date=26 February 2017 |accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Japan'''<ref name=\"Trophies\">{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/tadanari-lee/48599/ |title=Japan - T. Lee - Trophies |work=Soccerway |accessdate=5 October 2014 }}</ref>\n*[[AFC Asian Cup]]: [[2011 AFC Asian Cup|2011]]; runner-up: [[2019 AFC Asian Cup|2019]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of men's footballers with 100 or more international caps]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{FIFA player|271253}}\n*{{NFT player|pid=21533}}\n*{{J.League player|7876}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090324090607/http://nagoya-grampus.jp/clubteam/players/maya_yoshida.html Maya Yoshida] at Nagoya Grampus official site (2009) {{in lang|ja}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{U.C. Sampdoria squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Japan squads\n|bg= mediumblue\n|fg= white\n|bordercolor= red\n|list1=\n{{Japan men's football squad 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Japan squad 2011 AFC Asian Cup}}\n{{Japan men's football squad 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Japan squad 2013 FIFA Confederations Cup}}\n{{Japan squad 2014 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Japan squad 2015 AFC Asian Cup}}\n{{Japan squad 2018 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Japan squad 2019 AFC Asian Cup}}\n}}\n{{2019 AFC Asian Cup Team of the Tournament}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yoshida, Maya}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Association football people from Nagasaki Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Japanese footballers]]\n[[Category:Japan international footballers]]\n[[Category:J1 League players]]\n[[Category:Eredivisie players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Nagoya Grampus players]]\n[[Category:VVV-Venlo players]]\n[[Category:Southampton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:U.C. Sampdoria players]]\n[[Category:Olympic footballers of Japan]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:2011 AFC Asian Cup players]]\n[[Category:AFC Asian Cup-winning players]]\n[[Category:2013 FIFA Confederations Cup players]]\n[[Category:2014 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2015 AFC Asian Cup players]]\n[[Category:Japanese expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Japanese expatriate sportspeople in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Japanese expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:Japanese expatriate sportspeople in Italy]]\n[[Category:Association football central defenders]]\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2019 AFC Asian Cup players]]\n[[Category:FIFA Century Club]]\n", "name_user": "Ira Leviton", "label": "safe", "comment": "Deleted a duplicate \"the\".", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maya_Yoshida"}
{"title_page": "SHAKTI - Microprocessor & Microcontroller", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\nSHAKTI is the first opensource initiative by the Reconfigurable Intelligent Systems Engineering (RISE) group at [[Indian Institute of Technology Madras|Indian Institute of Technology, Madras]] to develop the first indigenous industrial-grade processor. The aim of SHAKTI initiative includes building an opensource production-grade processor, complete System on Chips (SoCs), development boards and SHAKTI based software platform. The primary focus of the team is architecture research to develop SoCs, which is competitive with commercial offerings in the market concerning area, power and performance. All the source codes for SHAKTI are open-sourced under the Modified BSD License of the University of California, Berkeley. The project was funded by [[Ministry of Electronics and Information Technology]] (MeITY), Government of India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/mobiles/news/iit-madras-develops-indias-first-microprocessor-shakti-1941909|title=IIT-Madras Develops 'India's First Microprocessor', Shakti|website=NDTV Gadgets 360|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n[[File:Shakti_microcontroller.png|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Shakti_microcontroller.png|alt=|thumb|A prototype version of the new shakti microcontroller.]]\n\n== Processors ==\n[https://shakti.org.in/ SHAKTI] processors are based on the [[RISC-V]] ISA. The processors are based on 22&nbsp;nm [[FinFET]] technology. SHAKTI has envisioned a family of processors as part of its road-map, catering to different segments of the market. They have been broadly categorized into \"Base Processors\", \"Multi-Core Processors\" and \"Experimental Processors\". The E and C-classes are the first set of indigenous processors aimed at Internet of Things (IoT), Embedded and Desktop markets. The processor design is free of any royalty and is open-sourced under the Modified BSD License.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gala|first=Neel|last2=Menon|first2=Arjun|last3=Bodduna|first3=Rahul|last4=Madhusudan|first4=G. S.|last5=Kamakoti|first5=V.|date=January 2016|title=SHAKTI Processors: An Open-Source Hardware Initiative|url=https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/7434907|journal=2016 29th International Conference on VLSI Design and 2016 15th International Conference on Embedded Systems (VLSID)|volume=|pages=7\u20138|doi=10.1109/VLSID.2016.130|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe SHAKTI project aims to build 6 variants of processors based on the RISC-V ISA.\n\n== Base Class Of Processors ==\n\n=== E-class ===\nThe E-class is 32/64 bit [[microcontroller]]s capable of supporting all extensions of RISC-V ISA, aimed at low-power and low compute applications. The E-class is an In-order 3 stage pipeline having an operational frequency of less than 200&nbsp;MHz on silicon. It is positioned against [[ARM architecture|ARM]]\u2019s M-class ([[ARM Cortex-M|CorTex-M]] series) cores. It's capable of running real-time operating systems like [[FreeRTOS]], [[Zephyr (operating system)|Zephyr]] and eChronos. Market segments of E-class processor support Smart-cards, IoT devices, motor controls and robotic platforms.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://shakti.org.in/docs/user_manual.pdf|title=SHAKTI DEVELOPMENT BOARD USER MANUAL|last=|first=|date=|website=SHAKTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 April 2010}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://engineersasylum.com/t/shakti-the-open-source-indian-microprocessor-microcontroller/664|title=Shakti - The Open Source Indian Microprocessor & Microcontroller|date=2020-04-07|website=Engineer's Asylum|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nE-arty35T is an SoC built around E-class. The E-arty35T SoC is a single-chip 32-bit E-class microcontroller with 128kB RAM. It has 32 General Purpose Input Output (GPIO) pins (out of which upper 16 GPIO pins are dedicated to onboard LEDs and switches), a Platform Level Interrupt Controller (PLIC), a Counter, 2 Serial Peripheral (SPI), 2 Universal Asynchronous Receiver Transmitter (UART), 1  Inter-Integrated Circuit (I2C), 6 Pulse Width Modulator (PWM) and an inbuilt Xilinx Analog to Digital Converter( X-ADC).<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=https://gitlab.com/shaktiproject/cores/shakti-soc/tree/master/fpga/boards/artya7-35t/e-class|title=E-Class on ARTY-A7-35t Board|last=|first=|date=|website=GitLab|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n=== C-class ===\nThe C-class is a 64-bit controller class of processor, aimed at mid-range embedded application. The core is highly optimized, 6-stage in-order design with MMU support and capability to run operating systems like Linux and Sel4. It's extremely configurable with the support of the standard RV64GC ISA extensions. It targets the mid-range compute systems running over 200-800&nbsp;MHz. It can also be customized up to 2&nbsp;GHz. It's positioned against ARM's Cortex A35/A55. The application domain of this class ranges from embedded systems, motor-control, IoT, storage, industrial applications to low-cost high-performance Linux based applications such as networking, gateways etc.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":12\" />\n\nC-arty100T is a SoC build around C-class. The C-arty100T SoC is a single-chip 64-bit C-class microcontroller with 128MB DDR3 RAM, 16 General Purpose Input Output (GPIO) pins, a Platform Level Interrupt Controller (PLIC), a Counter, 1 Universal Asynchronous Receiver Transmitter (UART) and 1 Inter-Integrated Circuit (I2C). It is aimed at mid-range application workloads with  a very low power consumption and has support for optional memory protection.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://gitlab.com/shaktiproject/cores/shakti-soc/tree/master/fpga/boards/artya7-100t/c-class|title=C-Class on ARTY-A7-100t Board|last=|first=|date=|website=GitLab|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n=== I-class ===\nThe I-class is a 64-bit processor which targets the compute, mobile, storage and networking platforms. Its features include [[out-of-order execution]], [[Multithreading (computer architecture)|multithreading]], aggressive [[Branch predictor|branch prediction]], [[non-blocking cache]]s and [[Deep pipelining|deep pipeline]] stages. The operational clock frequency of this processor is 1.5-2.5&nbsp;GHz. The team is currently working on implementing atomics, Memory dependence prediction, Instruction Window/Scheduler optimizations, Implementation of some functional units, Performance analysis/projections, Optimizations to meet first-cut target frequency on 1&nbsp;GHz on 22&nbsp;nm processor.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":42\">{{Cite web|url=https://shakti.org.in/processors.html|title=Processors|last=|first=|date=|website=SHAKTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shakti.org.in/docs/shaktiweek-i-class.pdf|title=Shakti I Class: Introduction|last=Ranganathan|first=Nitya|date=|website=SHAKTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Multicore Processors ==\n\n=== M-class ===\nA mobile class processor with a maximum of 8 cores, the cores being a combination of C and I class cores. The M-class processors are aimed at general-purpose compute, low-end server and mobile applications. The operation frequency ranges up to 2.5&nbsp;GHz. Its supports large issue size, quad-threaded & optional NoC fabric. The M-class processors are optimised for various power and performance targets.<ref name=\":42\" />\n\n=== S-class ===\nThe S-Class is a 64-bit [[Superscalar processor|superscalar]],[[multi-threaded]] variant aimed at Desktop and Enterprise server Application. Its supports 2-16 cores with a clock frequency of about 1.2\u20133&nbsp;GHz.<ref name=\":42\" />\n\n=== H-class ===\nThe H-class is a 64-bit processor aimed at highly parallel enterprise, HPC and analytics applications. The cores can be a combination of C or I class, single-thread performance driving the core choice. The H-class has up to 128 cores with multiple accelerators per core.<ref name=\":42\" />\n\n== Experimental Processors ==\nThese are experimental/research projects which focus on developing a high security and fault tolerant processor.\n\n=== T-class ===\nThe T-class is aimed to provide additional hardware support for securing information from memory-based attacks. Its design focus on a unified hardware framework for mitigating spatial and temporal memory attacks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.1145/3092627.3092629|title=Shakti-T {{!}} Proceedings of the Hardware and Architectural Support for Security and Privacy|website=dl.acm.org|language=EN|doi=10.1145/3092627.3092629|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n=== F-class ===\nThe F-class is a fault-tolerant version of the base class processor. Features include redundant compute blocks (like DMR and TMR), temporal redundancy modules to detect permanent faults, lock-step core configurations, fault localization circuits, ECC for critical memory blocks and redundant bus fabrics.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gupta|first=Sukrat|last2=Gala|first2=Neel|last3=Madhusudan|first3=G. S.|last4=Kamakoti|first4=V.|date=November 2015|title=SHAKTI-F: A Fault Tolerant Microprocessor Architecture|url=https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/7422253|journal=2015 IEEE 24th Asian Test Symposium (ATS)|volume=|pages=163\u2013168|doi=10.1109/ATS.2015.35|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Tapeouts ==\nTwo tapeouts of the C-class processors have been performed. They have been codenamed as RIMO and Rise-creek.\n\n=== RIMO ===\nRIMO is the code name of the SHAKTI C-class based SoC that has been tapeout at Semiconductor Laboratory (SCL) Indian Space Research Organizations (ISRO) at Chandigarh using 180&nbsp;nm process technology. The 144 sq.mm. chip has been tested to operate at a frequency of up to 70&nbsp;MHz. The chip has been packaged on a 208-pin Ceramic Quad Flat Pack (CQFP).<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n=== Risecreek ===\nCREEK is the code name of the SHAKTI C-class based SoC that has been taped-out at [[Intel|INTEL]], Oregon, the USA using 22&nbsp;nm process technology. The 16 sq.mm. chip has been tested to operate at a frequency of up to 350&nbsp;MHz. The chip has been packaged on a 208-pin Ball Grid Array (BGA)<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n== Features of RIMO and Risecreek ==\nSome of the features of RIMO and Risecreek are as follows:\n\n* In-order 5 stage 64-bit [[microcontroller]] supporting the entire stable RISC-V ISA(RV64IMAFD).\n* Compatible with privilege spec (v1.10) of RISC-V ISA and supports the sv39 virtualisation scheme.\n* Includes a branch predictor with a Return-Address-Stack.\n* Pipelined IEEE-754 compliant single and double-precision floating point units and Multi-channel [[Direct memory access|Direct Memory Access]] (DMA) support.\n* Peripherals like 2 x [[I\u00b2C|I2C]], 2 x [[Universal asynchronous receiver-transmitter|UART]], 2 x [[Serial Peripheral Interface|QSPI]], a [[Debugger]], a 256KB tightly coupled memory, 32-bit GPIOs and an expansion bus that can be connected to an [[Field-programmable gate array|FPGA]].<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n== Development boards ==\nThere are development boards for both E and C class of processors. The details on the board support for different classes of processors are given below.\n\n=== E-arty35T ===\n\n* E-arty35Tis a SoC based on SHAKTI E class [14].\n* E-arty35Tis supported on Artix 7 35T board.\n* It has an abridged version of 32 bit E class. It includes I, M, A and C.<ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== C-arty100T ===\n\n* C-arty100Tis a SoC based on SHAKTI C class.\n* C-arty100Tis supported on Artix 7 100T board.\n* It has an abridged version of 64 bit C class. It includes I, M, A, F, D and C.<ref name=\":32\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Microcontrollers]]\n[[Category:Microprocessors]]\n[[Category:Computer engineering]]\n[[Category:Embedded systems]]\n[[Category:India]]\n[[Category:Computing]]\n[[Category:Electronics]]\n[[Category:Information technology]]\n", "text_old": "SHAKTI is the first opensource initiative by the Reconfigurable Intelligent Systems Engineering (RISE) group at [[Indian Institute of Technology Madras|Indian Institute of Technology, Madras]] to develop the first indigenous industrial-grade processor. The aim of SHAKTI initiative includes building an opensource production-grade processor, complete System on Chips (SoCs), development boards and SHAKTI based software platform. The primary focus of the team is architecture research to develop SoCs, which is competitive with commercial offerings in the market concerning area, power and performance. All the source codes for SHAKTI are open-sourced under the Modified BSD License of the University of California, Berkeley. The project was funded by [[Ministry of Electronics and Information Technology]] (MeITY), Government of India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/mobiles/news/iit-madras-develops-indias-first-microprocessor-shakti-1941909|title=IIT-Madras Develops 'India's First Microprocessor', Shakti|website=NDTV Gadgets 360|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n[[File:Shakti_microcontroller.png|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Shakti_microcontroller.png|alt=|thumb|A prototype version of the new shakti microcontroller.]]\n\n== Processors ==\n[https://shakti.org.in/ SHAKTI] processors are based on the [[RISC-V]] ISA. The processors are based on 22nm [[FinFET]] technology. SHAKTI has envisioned a family of processors as part of its road-map, catering to different segments of the market. They have been broadly categorized into \"Base Processors\", \"Multi-Core Processors\" and \"Experimental Processors\". The E and C-classes are the first set of indigenous processors aimed at Internet of Things (IoT), Embedded and Desktop markets. The processor design is free of any royalty and is open-sourced under the Modified BSD License.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gala|first=Neel|last2=Menon|first2=Arjun|last3=Bodduna|first3=Rahul|last4=Madhusudan|first4=G. S.|last5=Kamakoti|first5=V.|date=January 2016|title=SHAKTI Processors: An Open-Source Hardware Initiative|url=https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/7434907|journal=2016 29th International Conference on VLSI Design and 2016 15th International Conference on Embedded Systems (VLSID)|volume=|pages=7\u20138|doi=10.1109/VLSID.2016.130|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe SHAKTI project aims to build 6 variants of processors based on the RISC-V ISA.\n\n== Base Class Of Processors ==\n\n=== E-class ===\nThe E-class is 32/64 bit [[Microcontroller|microcontrollers]] capable of supporting all extensions of RISC-V ISA, aimed at low-power and low compute applications. The E-class is an In-order 3 stage pipeline having an operational frequency of less than 200MHz on silicon. It is positioned against [[ARM architecture|ARM]]\u2019s M-class ([[ARM Cortex-M|CorTex-M]] series) cores. It's capable of running real-time operating systems like [[FreeRTOS]], [[Zephyr (operating system)|Zephyr]] and eChronos. Market segments of E-class processor support Smart-cards, IoT devices, motor controls and robotic platforms.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://shakti.org.in/docs/user_manual.pdf|title=SHAKTI DEVELOPMENT BOARD USER MANUAL|last=|first=|date=|website=SHAKTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 April 2010}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://engineersasylum.com/t/shakti-the-open-source-indian-microprocessor-microcontroller/664|title=Shakti - The Open Source Indian Microprocessor & Microcontroller|date=2020-04-07|website=Engineer's Asylum|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nE-arty35T is an SoC built around E-class. The E-arty35T SoC is a single-chip 32-bit E-class microcontroller with 128kB RAM. It has 32 General Purpose Input Output (GPIO) pins (out of which upper 16 GPIO pins are dedicated to onboard LEDs and switches), a Platform Level Interrupt Controller (PLIC), a Counter, 2 Serial Peripheral (SPI), 2 Universal Asynchronous Receiver Transmitter (UART), 1  Inter-Integrated Circuit (I2C), 6 Pulse Width Modulator (PWM) and an inbuilt Xilinx Analog to Digital Converter( X-ADC).<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=https://gitlab.com/shaktiproject/cores/shakti-soc/tree/master/fpga/boards/artya7-35t/e-class|title=E-Class on ARTY-A7-35t Board|last=|first=|date=|website=GitLab|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n=== C-class ===\nThe C-class is a 64-bit controller class of processor, aimed at mid-range embedded application. The core is highly optimized, 6-stage in-order design with MMU support and capability to run operating systems like Linux and Sel4. It's extremely configurable with the support of the standard RV64GC ISA extensions. It targets the mid-range compute systems running over 200-800MHz. It can also be customized up to 2 GHz. It's positioned against ARM's Cortex A35/A55. The application domain of this class ranges from embedded systems, motor-control, IoT, storage, industrial applications to low-cost high-performance Linux based applications such as networking, gateways etc.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":12\" />\n\nC-arty100T is a SoC build around C-class. The C-arty100T SoC is a single-chip 64-bit C-class microcontroller with 128MB DDR3 RAM, 16 General Purpose Input Output (GPIO) pins, a Platform Level Interrupt Controller (PLIC), a Counter, 1 Universal Asynchronous Receiver Transmitter (UART) and 1 Inter-Integrated Circuit (I2C). It is aimed at mid-range application workloads with  a very low power consumption and has support for optional memory protection.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://gitlab.com/shaktiproject/cores/shakti-soc/tree/master/fpga/boards/artya7-100t/c-class|title=C-Class on ARTY-A7-100t Board|last=|first=|date=|website=GitLab|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n=== I-class ===\nThe I-class is a 64-bit processor which targets the compute, mobile, storage and networking platforms. Its features include [[out-of-order execution]], [[Multithreading (computer architecture)|multithreading]], aggressive [[Branch predictor|branch prediction]], [[Non-blocking cache|non-blocking caches]] and [[Deep pipelining|deep pipeline]] stages. The operational clock frequency of this processor is 1.5-2.5 GHz. The team is currently working on implementing atomics, Memory dependence prediction, Instruction Window/Scheduler optimizations, Implementation of some functional units, Performance analysis/projections, Optimizations to meet first-cut target frequency on 1 GHz on 22nm processor.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":42\">{{Cite web|url=https://shakti.org.in/processors.html|title=Processors|last=|first=|date=|website=SHAKTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shakti.org.in/docs/shaktiweek-i-class.pdf|title=Shakti I Class: Introduction|last=Ranganathan|first=Nitya|date=|website=SHAKTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Multicore Processors ==\n\n=== M-class ===\nA mobile class processor with a maximum of 8 cores, the cores being a combination of C and I class cores. The M-class processors are aimed at general-purpose compute, low-end server and mobile applications. The operation frequency ranges up to 2.5 GHz. Its supports large issue size, quad-threaded & optional NoC fabric. The M-class processors are optimised for various power and performance targets.<ref name=\":42\" />\n\n=== S-class ===\nThe S-Class is a 64-bit [[Superscalar processor|superscalar]],[[multi-threaded]] variant aimed at Desktop and Enterprise server Application. Its supports 2-16 cores with a clock frequency of about 1.2-3 GHz.<ref name=\":42\" />\n\n=== H-class ===\nThe H-class is a 64-bit processor aimed at highly parallel enterprise, HPC and analytics applications. The cores can be a combination of C or I class, single-thread performance driving the core choice. The H-class has up to 128 cores with multiple accelerators per core.<ref name=\":42\" />\n\n== Experimental Processors ==\nThese are experimental/research projects which focus on developing a high security and fault tolerant processor.\n\n=== T-class ===\nThe T-class is aimed to provide additional hardware support for securing information from memory-based attacks. Its design focus on a unified hardware framework for mitigating spatial and temporal memory attacks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.1145/3092627.3092629|title=Shakti-T {{!}} Proceedings of the Hardware and Architectural Support for Security and Privacy|website=dl.acm.org|language=EN|doi=10.1145/3092627.3092629|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n=== F-class ===\nThe F-class is a fault-tolerant version of the base class processor. Features include redundant compute blocks (like DMR and TMR), temporal redundancy modules to detect permanent faults, lock-step core configurations, fault localization circuits, ECC for critical memory blocks and redundant bus fabrics.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gupta|first=Sukrat|last2=Gala|first2=Neel|last3=Madhusudan|first3=G. S.|last4=Kamakoti|first4=V.|date=November 2015|title=SHAKTI-F: A Fault Tolerant Microprocessor Architecture|url=https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/7422253|journal=2015 IEEE 24th Asian Test Symposium (ATS)|volume=|pages=163\u2013168|doi=10.1109/ATS.2015.35|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Tapeouts ==\nTwo tapeouts of the C-class processors have been performed. They have been codenamed as RIMO and Rise-creek.\n\n=== RIMO ===\nRIMO is the code name of the SHAKTI C-class based SoC that has been tapeout at Semiconductor Laboratory (SCL) Indian Space Research Organizations (ISRO) at Chandigarh using 180 nm process technology. The 144 sq.mm. chip has been tested to operate at a frequency of up to 70 MHz. The chip has been packaged on a 208-pin Ceramic Quad Flat Pack (CQFP).<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n=== Risecreek ===\nCREEK is the code name of the SHAKTI C-class based SoC that has been taped-out at [[Intel|INTEL]], Oregon, the USA using 22 nm process technology. The 16 sq.mm. chip has been tested to operate at a frequency of up to 350 MHz. The chip has been packaged on a 208-pin Ball Grid Array (BGA)<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n== Features of RIMO and Risecreek ==\nSome of the features of RIMO and Risecreek are as follows:\n\n* In-order 5 stage 64-bit [[microcontroller]] supporting the entire stable RISC-V ISA(RV64IMAFD).\n* Compatible with privilege spec (v1.10) of RISC-V ISA and supports the sv39 virtualisation scheme.\n* Includes a branch predictor with a Return-Address-Stack.\n* Pipelined IEEE-754 compliant single and double-precision floating point units and Multi-channel [[Direct memory access|Direct Memory Access]] (DMA) support.\n* Peripherals like 2 x [[I\u00b2C|I2C]], 2 x [[Universal asynchronous receiver-transmitter|UART]], 2 x [[Serial Peripheral Interface|QSPI]], a [[Debugger]], a 256KB tightly coupled memory, 32-bit GPIOs and an expansion bus that can be connected to an [[Field-programmable gate array|FPGA]].<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n== Development boards ==\nThere are development boards for both E and C class of processors. The details on the board support for different classes of processors are given below.\n\n=== E-arty35T ===\n\n* E-arty35Tis a SoC based on SHAKTI E class [14].\n* E-arty35Tis supported on Artix 7 35T board.\n* It has an abridged version of 32 bit E class. It includes I, M, A and C.<ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== C-arty100T ===\n\n* C-arty100Tis a SoC based on SHAKTI C class.\n* C-arty100Tis supported on Artix 7 100T board.\n* It has an abridged version of 64 bit C class. It includes I, M, A, F, D and C.<ref name=\":32\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Microcontrollers]]\n[[Category:Microprocessors]]\n[[Category:Computer engineering]]\n[[Category:Embedded systems]]\n[[Category:India]]\n[[Category:Computing]]\n[[Category:Electronics]]\n[[Category:Information technology]]\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, addedorphantag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHAKTI_-_Microprocessor_%26_Microcontroller"}
{"title_page": "Manny Charlton", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Manny Charlton\n| image               = Nazareth 03121976 01 640.jpg\n| caption             = Charlton in 1976.\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| years_active        = 1958&ndash;present \n| genre               = [[Hard rock]], [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]], [[blues rock]], [[pop rock]]\n|birth_name = Manuel Charlton\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1941|7|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[La L\u00ednea de la Concepci\u00f3n|La L\u00ednea]], [[Andalusia]], [[Spain]]\n| origin         = [[Dunfermline, Scotland]]\n| instrument          = {{flatlist|\n* [[Guitar]]\n* [[Singing|vocals]]\n}}\n| associated_acts     = [[Nazareth (band)|Nazareth]], [[Manny Charlton Band]], From Behind \n| website             = [http://mannycharltonband.com/ Mannycharltonband.com]\n}}\n\n'''Manuel \"Manny\" Charlton''' (born 25 July 1941, [[La L\u00ednea de la Concepci\u00f3n|La L\u00ednea]], [[Andalusia]], southern Spain) is a founding member of the Scottish [[hard rock]] band [[Nazareth (band)|Nazareth]] and was their lead guitarist from 1968 to 1990.\n\n==Career==\n===Nazareth===\nCharlton's family had emigrated from [[Spain]] to [[Dunfermline]], [[Scotland]] in the 1940s when he was aged 2. Prior to joining Nazareth, Charlton played in a few bands, most notably the Mark 5 and later the Red Hawks, until joining the local semi-pro Dunfermline band The Shadettes. In 1968, the band changed their name to ''Nazareth'', inspired by the opening lyric from \"[[The Weight]]\", a song by [[The Band]].\n\nCharlton played a huge part in Nazareth's worldwide success. His [[blues music|blues]]y style of playing, combined with [[Dan McCafferty]]'s vocals, first came to the attention of wider rock audiences when Nazareth toured in 1971 as the opening act for [[Deep Purple]]. But by 1973, they were headlining their own shows.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abc.eznettools.net/rocknresort/08-nazareth-manny-charlton.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-11-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011073709/http://abc.eznettools.net/rocknresort/08-nazareth-manny-charlton.html |archivedate=2008-10-11 }} </ref> Charlton also became the band's [[record producer|producer]] for many years, succeeding Deep Purple's [[Roger Glover]], after the band decided they wanted to move in a new direction for the ''[[Hair of the Dog (album)|Hair of the Dog]]'' album. ''Hair of the Dog'' attained [[music recording sales certification|platinum]] sales in the [[United States]] and has to date sold in excess of two million copies. It is the band's most well known album, and contains their biggest ever hit \"Love Hurts\" which reached No. 8 in the US. Charlton also produced the self-titled ''Dan McCafferty'' debut [[Gramophone record|LP]] around this time.\n\n===''Appetite For Destruction''===\n[[Axl Rose]] of [[Guns N' Roses]] initially wanted \"the producer of Nazareth's Hair of the Dog\"{{citation needed | date=May 2015}} to produce what would become the band's breakthrough album. Manny Charlton subsequently got the request from Geffen Records and did produce several performances recorded at Sound City (LA) on 4 June 1986.  The songs include \"Paradise City\", two versions of \"Move to the City\", \"November Rain\", \"Shadow of your Love\" (takes one and two), and  \"Reckless Life\". However, after the initial work, Nazareth duties were pressing for  Charlton to return to Europe, and Guns N Roses eventually hired Mike Clink to produce the album. Charlton's productions were included as a bonus disc on the 2018 re-issue of ''[[Appetite for Destruction]]''.\n\n===Exit from Nazareth===\nAfter leaving Nazareth in 1990, Charlton played some [[solo (music)|solo]] [[concert|shows]] on the [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[nightclub|club]] circuit, and released his first solo album ''Drool'' in 1997, on the Red Steel [[record label]] with Neil Miller on vocals. The following year, he relocated to [[Texas]], where he formed the [[Manny Charlton Band]] (MCB). The new band released a pair of albums &ndash; ''Stonkin'' and ''Klone This'' &ndash; before disbanding in 2003.\n\n===''Doom''===\nIn 1995, Charlton sent to [[id Software]], creator of ''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]'', a cassette tape featuring an untitled song that [[John Romero]] would later title \"Blood on the Walls\". The liner said, \"For all the guys and gals at I.D. (sic) who came up with the coolest game this side of hell, kick some demon butt to this!!\" It also said \"distribute as [[shareware]]\", in keeping with the old days of PC gaming in which one could get the first third or fourth of the game for free or a reduced price, and buy the full game later.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} Romero would later find this tape and record it to mp3, providing it for free on his website. The song is actually titled \"Doom\" from Charlton's album ''Drool''.\n\n===Recent work===\nIn 2004, Charlton released ''Say The Word'' on the Scottish label River Records. 2005 saw the release of ''Sharp'', which is on the whole a [[cover version|covers]] album, including [[Tim Hardin]]'s \"Hang On To A Dream\" and [[Bob Dylan]]'s \"Shelter From The Storm\". Later that year, Charlton completed the follow-up to ''Sharp'', titled  ''Sharp Re-Loaded''. \n\nIn early 2006, Charlton joined the Swedish rock band, From Behind, who released their debut album titled ''Game Over'', and toured in support of the album around [[Europe]] before disbanding in late 2007. Charlton then released a solo album ''Americana Deluxe'', covering songs such as [[Fleetwood Mac]]'s \"Tusk\".\n\nIn March 2013, Charlton released ''Hellacious''.<ref name=\"Hellacious, cdbaby\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cdbaby.com/cd/mannycharltonband1|title=\u266b Hellacious - The Manny Charlton Band|website=Cdbaby.com|accessdate=18 August 2017}}</ref> co-produced by Gary Bryant (GB Records). This recording was made in California and featured  \n[[Tim Bogert]], [[Walfredo Reyes, Jr.]], [[Steven Adler]], [[Vivian Campbell]] and Robyn DeLarenzo.\n\nIn 2014, Charlton's solo albums ''Sharp'' and ''Sharp Re-Loaded'' were issued as a double CD.  Neil Jefferies of ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]'' commended Charlton's production work, writing: \"Among three Dylan songs tackled, All Along The Watchtower is simply stunning, sidestepping both the original and Hendrix\u2019s seminal version with quasi-reggae tones that cement Charlton\u2019s reputation as a truly gifted arranger.\"\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Nazareth discography}}\n<!-- DO NOT ADD DETAILS TO THIS LIST - Edit separate Nazareth discography article instead! -->\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* ''[[Nazareth (album)|Nazareth]]'' (1971)\n* ''[[Exercises (album)|Exercises]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Razamanaz]]'' (1973)\n* ''[[Loud 'n' Proud]]'' (1973)\n* ''[[Rampant (album)|Rampant]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[Hair of the Dog (album)|Hair of the Dog]]'' (1975)\n* ''[[Close Enough for Rock 'n' Roll]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[Play 'n' the Game]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[Expect No Mercy]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[No Mean City (album)|No Mean City]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Malice in Wonderland (Nazareth album)|Malice in Wonderland]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[The Fool Circle]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[2XS]]'' (1982)\n* ''[[Sound Elixir]]'' (1983)\n* ''[[The Catch (album)|The Catch]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[Cinema (Nazareth album)|Cinema]]'' (1986)\n* ''[[Snakes 'n' Ladders]]'' (1989)\n}}\n\n===Solo===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* ''Manny Charlton - Drool'' (1999)\n* ''Manny Charlton - Bravado'' (2000)\n* ''Manny Charlton Band \u2013 Stonkin\u2019'' (2002)\n* ''Manny Charlton Band \u2013 Klone This'' (2003)\n* ''Manny Charlton \u2013 Say The Word'' (2004)\n* ''Manny Charlton - Sharp'' (2004)\n* ''Manny Charlton \u2013 Sharp Re-Loaded'' (2005)\n* ''From Behind \u2013 Game Over'' (2006)\n* ''Manny Charlton \u2013 Americana Deluxe'' (2007)\n* ''Manny Charlton \u2013 Then There\u2019s This'' (2008)\n* ''Manny Charlton Band - Hellacious'' (2013)\n* ''Manny Charlton - Sharp / Sharp Re-Loaded (2CD Reissue)'' (2014)\n* ''Manny Charlton - Solo'' (2016)\n}}\n\n===Singles===\n\n* \"Manny Charlton Band - It Does Something\" (2012)\n\n===ROIO===\n\n* ''Nazareth with Manny Charlton \u2013 Rock \u2018N\u2019 Roll Resort (Live)'' (2008)\n\n===Contributions===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* ''Marseille \u2013 Red, White and Slightly Blue'' (1977)\n* ''Guns N Roses \u2013 Appetite For Destruction'' (1986) - pre-production\n* ''Jingo De Lunch \u2013 B.Y.E'' (1992) \n* ''Various Artists \u2013 A Tribute To Led Zeppelin'' (2008)\n* ''Robin DeLorenzo \u2013 Walkin' Miles in My Shoes'' (2014)\n* ''The Fluffy Jackets \u2013 Fighting Demons'' (2014) \n* ''The Mighty Mojos \u2013 Mojo Rising (EP)'' (2015)\n* ''Billy Craig \u2013 Another Lazy Day'' (2015)\n* ''[[Salem (UK band)|Salem (UK)]] - Tank on the album Dark Days'' (2016)\n* ''The Fluffy Jackets feat. Manny Charlton \u2013 Something from Nothing (CD + DVD)'' (2019) \n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mannycharltonband.com Official Manny Charlton website]\n*{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p63911|label=Manny Charlton}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070323112904/http://rome.ro/games_doom.htm John Romero's Doom page] features a section on MCB's gift to id Software and accompanying mp3 and a scan of the liner\n\n{{Nazareth}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Charlton, Manny}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Spanish emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Scottish rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:Male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Scottish heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:Nazareth (band) members]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Manny Charlton\n| image               = Nazareth 03121976 01 640.jpg\n| caption             = Charlton in 1976.\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| years_active        = 1958&ndash;present \n| genre               = [[Hard rock]], [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]], [[blues rock]], [[pop rock]]\n|birth_name = Manuel Charlton\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1941|7|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[La L\u00ednea de la Concepci\u00f3n|La L\u00ednea]], [[Andalusia]], [[Spain]]\n| origin         = [[Dunfermline, Scotland]]\n| instrument          = {{flatlist|\n* [[Guitar]]\n* [[Singing|vocals]]\n}}\n| associated_acts     = [[Nazareth (band)|Nazareth]]\n| website             = [http://mannycharltonband.com/ Mannycharltonband.com]\n}}\n\n'''Manuel \"Manny\" Charlton''' (born 25 July 1941, [[La L\u00ednea de la Concepci\u00f3n|La L\u00ednea]], [[Andalusia]], southern Spain) is a founding member of the Scottish [[hard rock]] band [[Nazareth (band)|Nazareth]] and was their lead guitarist from 1968 to 1990.\n\n==Career==\n===Nazareth===\nCharlton's family had emigrated from [[Spain]] to [[Dunfermline]], [[Scotland]] in the 1940s when he was aged 2. Prior to joining Nazareth, Charlton played in a few bands, most notably the Mark 5 and later the Red Hawks, until joining the local semi-pro Dunfermline band The Shadettes. In 1968, the band changed their name to ''Nazareth'', inspired by the opening lyric from \"[[The Weight]]\", a song by [[The Band]].\n\nCharlton played a huge part in Nazareth's worldwide success. His [[blues music|blues]]y style of playing, combined with [[Dan McCafferty]]'s vocals, first came to the attention of wider rock audiences when Nazareth toured in 1971 as the opening act for [[Deep Purple]]. But by 1973, they were headlining their own shows.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abc.eznettools.net/rocknresort/08-nazareth-manny-charlton.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-11-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011073709/http://abc.eznettools.net/rocknresort/08-nazareth-manny-charlton.html |a